		<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - BARD</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>BARD 101</font> - <small>Danthia Dylsherica, Solusek Ro</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>So you decided to be a bard. 
<P>
Congratulations, you’ve just chosen the most fun and most complicated class in EQ.  No other class has the variety of abilities that the bard class offers, or the options the bard has for fighting. 
<P>
Bard 101 is a 'How to get started' guide on the basics of bardic life.  It covers the things young  bards need to know and offers advice on how to play the first 10 levels. You will learn about songs, twisting, juggling, hot keying and some basic bard tactics.
<P>
<u><b>
Songs</b><br>
</u>Songs are the bards arsenal and what makes them unique. Songs differ from spells in many ways. First, songs can be sung or 'cast' while moving. They also stay 'on' and continue to work (with a few exceptions) until the bard stops singing. Most importantly, bards can 'twist' their songs to sing three at once, aiding the bard or group extremely well.
<P>
Bards get one song per level, and unlike casters, their songs are unique. Bards do not get 'upgrades' to their songs every four levels. (There are a few exceptions to this, such as the haste songs). So the song you got at first level is just as usuable at 50th level. Most songs increase in power as you level, making them viable throughout your bardic career. As you gain songs, it is important to experiment with what they do and how they work with your other songs. I keep a reference sheet by my PC with all of my songs and a brief description of what they do. I find it very handy.
<P>
Don't be afraid to experiment with your songs. They are what makes a bard a bard, and by using them you become more effective than by not. Songs aren't just to make you better. They make the whole PARTY better. Different groups need different tactics. There is no 'perfect' way to play.
<P>
<u><b>
Instruments</b><br>
</u>A bard has four instruments available: Percussion (Drum), Wind (Flute), String (Lute or Mandolin) and Brass (Horn). Depending on the song, these instruments give added bonuses. Each song will state what instrument it needs. Some only require singing, and some require the instrument to be equipped to sing it at all. Chant of Battle is a percussion song, and it is more effective if you have a drum equipped when you sing it. It might add 8 points of strength just singing it, but 14 points if you sing with the drum equipped. You will run faster using Selo’s Accelerando with a drum than without. You heal more with the lute.
<P>
As you level, you will be able to fight using nothing but instruments equipped and songs.  You will need to learn how to 'juggle' instruments to get the maximum benefit from each song you’re singing.
<P>
<u><b>
Twisting</b></u><br>
Twisting means singing multiple songs to get multiple effects. Most songs last for three pulses, each pulse lasting 6 seconds. So you can sing three songs and have all three pusles working at the same time. 
<P>
It is a fairly simply thing, but it does take practice. The basics are:
1.  Click on your song to start it.
2.  Watch your text screen until you see the song effect ie; 'You feel your pulse quicken'
3.  Double click on the next song you want to sing. (You need 2 clicks, one to turn off the song you are currently singing, and one to start singing the new song).
4.  Watch your text screen for the new song effect, ie 'Your wounds begin to heal'
5.  Repeat until creature is dead.
<P>
Some songs do not last three pulses, but are a 'one shot deal' type of song. (The level 12 song, Brusco's Boastful Bellow does one hit of damage each time you sing. It is comparable to a warrior kick or bash, and it goes up as you level.) These songs can be twisted, they simply do not pulse.
<P>
<u><b>
Hot Keying Songs</b><br>
</u>Hot keying your songs is a must. It allows you to sing faster and easier, and during high volume lag it is often the only way you will even be able to sing. The basics are:
<ol>
  <li>  Go to your main screen with the OPTIONS button. </li>
  <li>Choose the song you wish to hotkey. It will be one of the 8 songs you have memorized on the left hand side of your screen. </li>
  <li>Left click for about 1 second on the song you want to hot key. The button should 'pop off' the screen and move with your cursor. </li>
  <li>Move it down to the bottom left hand corner panel to an empty slot on your hot key pad. (This is the 6 box panel on the side. You have 6 of these panels). </li>
  <li>The song will click in place and look like a button. You can access this by pressing a number on your keyborad. 1 to 6 starts the songs, the top left hand song being number 1, the top right hand song number 2 and so on.</li>
</ol>
<P>
You can twist these songs by pressing 1-22-33-11-22-33… over and over. You can use all 6 buttons and simply switch what you press. ie 2-33-44-22-33-44…
<P>
You can also switch between the 6 panels by pressing 'shift' + the number of the panel you want. This makes it easy to have hot key panels for twisting, for melee, for juggling and for common buttons and skills like sit, /who all, and sense heading.
<P>
<u><b>
Hot Keying Weapons/Instruments</b><br>
</u>You should also hot key your weapon and inventory slots. These are done in the same way, only you need to hit the 'I' (inventory) key to switch over from your character inventory screen to your panel screen. You will need to make a hot key for your primary and secondary weapons, and an empty inventory slot. I recommend buying a 6 slot bag and keeping all of your weapons and instruments in there. You can hot key that bag, and simply right click on it to access your weapons and instruments from the main play screen. Having the bag look different from your backpacks will make it easy to find in your inventory.
<P>
<u><b>
Juggling</b><br>
</u>Bards need to juggle both weapons and instruments to be at their peak. This can be tricky, but by hot keying you can manage easily enough. To juggle your instruments, the basics are:
<P>
<u><b>
Two Instruments</b></u>
<ol>
  <li>Equip the instrument you wish to use in your secondary melee slot. (melee number 2). </li>
  <li>Sing the song that uses that instrument. </li>
  <li>Pick up the next instrument you wish to use in your cursor.</li>
  <li>Hover it over the melee slot. </li>
  <li>Click on the melee slot. Your instruments should switch places. </li>
  <li>Sing the next song that uses that instrument. </li>
  <li>Repeat.</li>
</ol>
<P>
As you level you will want to juggle three instruments. You will need to have an open inventory slot next to your weapon slot. If you are worried about where to put the third instrument, have two empty inventory slots to place the last intrument in. Bards can no longer drop their weapons or instruments, and this will help you a lot in the early days.  For the example, I will use a drum, horn and lute to make it easy to follow.
<P>
<u><b>
Three Instruments</b></u>
<ol>
  <li>Put your third instrument (lute) in an empty inventory slot, hot keyed. </li>
  <li>Equip the instrument you wish to use (drum) in your secondary melee slot. (melee number 2). </li>
  <li>Sing the song that uses that instrument. </li>
  <li>Pick up the next instrument (horn) you wish to use in your cursor. </li>
  <li>Hover the horn over the melee slot. (drum). </li>
  <li>Click on the melee slot. Your instruments should switch places. (horn in melee, drum in cursor). </li>
  <li>Sing the next song that uses that instrument. </li>
  <li>Hover the cursor instrument (drum) over the inventory slot (lute). </li>
  <li>Click on lute and switch places. (drum in inventory, lute in cursor). </li>
  <li>Hover lute over melee slot. </li>
  <li>Click on melee slot and switch. (lute in melee, drum in cursor). </li>
  <li>Sing song that uses the lute. </li>
  <li>Repeat.</li>
</ol>
<P>
The same tactic can be used to switch from weapons to instruments. Most times you will switch to your lute between fights to heal, or the drum to make a speedy getaway.
<P>
<u><b>
Songs vs. Weapons</b><br>
</u>Bards are not warriors who can sing. They are singers who can fight. They don’t have the defense skills of real tanks, but can take damage fairly well. In the early levels, melee will serve you best, using songs to enhance your abilities. Both weapons and songs are viable tools. 
<P>
As you level, you must remember that not everything a bard does revolves around damage. Sometimes going full instrumental and singing a buff, a debuff and one damage song does more good that you hacking or singing damage. You need to learn what option is best for each situation. This comes with experience and is part of the fun of being a bard.
<P>
<u><b>
What Weapon to Use?</b><br>
</u>Bards can use one handed slashing, piercing and blunt. Use whichever of these you can find the best weapon of, but practice all three. Bards have a huge amount of weapons available to them, and you don’t want to be caught at level 40 getting a great blunt weapon that you have no skill in. If you don’t want to carry the weight of three weapons, keep two in the bank and switch whenever you do your banking until all your skills are maxed. Then just carry the best one for day to day fighting.
<P>
<u><b>
Using Your Songs</b><br>
</u>The first song you get is <b><a href='http://eq.castersrealm.com/spells/spelldescriptions.asp?Id=1024'> Chant of
Battle</a></b>. This song affects everyone in your group (including you) and is a buff. It increases your AC, strength and dexterity. Sing this song while you fight.
<P>
Next is <b><a href='http://eq.castersrealm.com/spells/spelldescriptions.asp?Id=1025'> Chords of
Dissonance</a></b>. This is an area affect damage over time (or DoT) song, so be very careful where you sing it. This song does a certain amount of damage over 3 pulses. (varries with level). Anything passing close to you will be hit by it and attack you. This includes guards and merchants. Twisting this song with Chant of Battle will buff you and do damage to the creature you are fighting. 
<P>
<b><a href='http://eq.castersrealm.com/spells/spelldescriptions.asp?Id=1026'>
Jaxan’s Jig of Vigor</a></b> is a stamina replenisher, and will give you back stamina (the yellow bar). This is helpful for long fights, while swimming or just keeping you alive if you forget to buy food. You can sing this song once when you are low on stamina and it will replensih it. You may only need to sing it once or twice in a fight. It does not have to be twisted into your 'battle twist', only sung in place of one of the songs every so often, if needed.
<P>
<b><a href='http://eq.castersrealm.com/spells/spelldescriptions.asp?Id=1027'>
Lyssa’s Locating Lyric</a></b> helps players who have lost their corpses. You click on the person you need to find the corpse for (yourself included) and sing this song. It 'snaps' you to face the direction of the body. Simply run to it. Be careful where you’re running, since you don’t want to run right through a camp of monsters or past a high level creature. This song is great for finding your own corpse, and for making friends. 
<P>
<b><a href='http://eq.castersrealm.com/spells/spelldescriptions.asp?Id=1028'>
Selo’s Accelerando</a></b> is one of the best bard songs. This is the speed song, and it makes you run faster. This song is great for traveling, pulling (finding a creature and bringing it back to your group) or fleeing. When you need to run, sing first and take off before switching from weapons to drum. Those extra seconds can save your life. While traveling with a group, try to stay in the back to keep everyone in range. Those that get ahead of you will fall back to regular speed, if out of range, and allow the rest to catch up.
<P>
<b><a href='http://eq.castersrealm.com/spells/spelldescriptions.asp?Id=1029'>
Hymn of Restoration</a></b> is the healing song, and is a vital song. Sing this in battle and you will gain health back during the fight. Equip the lute after the fight and you will heal up faster. Sitting helps healing even more. In a group, you can heal the party while everyone else is medding back their mana. This gives you less 'downtime' and lets you hunt more. By now, (level 6) you should be twisting Chant, Chords (if space permits) and Hymn. If three songs is too tricky still, pick two to twist until you get better at it.
<P>
<b><a href='http://eq.castersrealm.com/spells/spelldescriptions.asp?Id=1030'>
Jonathan’s Whistling Warsong</a></b> is the first of the haste songs, speeding your attacks, increasing your strength and AC. This song works only on you. Twist Jonathan’s with Hymn and either Chords or Chant. It doesn’t affect anyone else in your group, but it will make you a better fighter which is good for the group. If solo, Chords is good, in a group Chant will help everyone. 
<P>
<b><a href='http://eq.castersrealm.com/spells/spelldescriptions.asp?Id=1031'>
Kelin’s Lugubrious Lament</a></b> is a 'lull' type song. This will make the creatures so sad they won’t feel like attacking you. You target the creature you don’t want to attack and sing this. This is best for pulling a single creature out of a camp of several. Be warned however, this song can fail and the whole camp will come at you. This is when you hit Selo’s and run for the zone, or dig in with your group and hope for the best. For best results, use the lute when singing this song to improve your chances of lulling the creature. Switch back to weapons before the pull.
<P>
<b><a href='http://eq.castersrealm.com/spells/spelldescriptions.asp?Id=1032'>
Elemental Rhythms</a></b> is your first resistance buff. It increases magic resistance, cold restsance, fire resistance and AC. It is good for when you are fighting casters that keep hitting you with spells. Twisting this with Hymn and either Chant or Jonathan’s is a good trio when fighting casting creatures.
<P>
<b><a href='http://eq.castersrealm.com/spells/spelldescriptions.asp?Id=1033'>
Anthem de Arms</a></b> is your first party haste buff. This increases everyone’s attacks and strength. By now (level 10) this should be sung in every group fight, twisted with Hymn and either Chords, Rhythms or Chant. The situation will tell you which of these three to sing. When you solo, still use Jonathan’s, since the haste is better. Or if you are in a group where you are the only melee class. Otherwise, Anthem is a great party benefiting song.
<P>
<u><b>
Things to Remember</b></u>
<P>
<i>Tanking, Taunt and Aggro</i><P>
Since bards are not true tanks, they have to be smart. Our songs tend to get the creatures very upset. This is what is refered to as a 'high taunt factor'. They don’t like us helping so many people at once and that tends to make them want to hit us more. They will run right past other players just to hit you. This is called 'aggro' and can be a problem. When you’re in a fight (in a group), and you start taking a lot of damage, back off and stop attacking for a few seconds. I know this sounds strange, but trust me. The warrior is better suited to take damage than you are. Let the creature get mad at him and then resume fighting. The creature should turn to the warrior/tank right away. If you are the only tank, this does not apply. You are there to take the damage.  There are times when you will WANT to get the creatures attention on you (frail casters are getting pulverized) and songs like Chords, Hymn and Lament can help.
<P>
<i>
Versatility</i><P>
Bards are the single most versatile class in the game. We can sing, fight, buff, de-buff, heal, damage and look great doing it. You can chose to play your bard in many ways. Some like the melee approach and focus on damage. Some like the buffing aspects and play more defensively. Others like to fill the gap and do whatever needs doing at that given time. Be flexible and try new things. What works with a caster heavy group may not with a melee heavy group. Some songs work great with certain spells, some cancel other spells out (usually not a good thing). Never be afraid to experiment.
<P>
<i>
Mana</i><P>
Bards don’t need mana to sing, but many non-bards don’t know this. Often in a group someone will tell you to save your mana and not to heal them when you sing Hymn. Just explain to them how bard songs work and be proud. A lot of what bards do is 'behind the scenes' and people don’t realize how helpful they are to a group. Let them know. Also, a common myth is that Jig helps regain mana faster. This is untrue. 
<P>
<i>
Spare Instruments</i><P>
I always have a spare instrument of each type in the bank. When you die far away and have to run all the way back, you will be happy you have a drum in the bank. Later, when you need invisibility to get to your body, you will need that flute. Spares make it a lot easier. Just remember to put them back.
<P>
This concludes Bard 101. I hope you’ve found this information helpful. Though challenging, bards are the most rewarding class to play and the most group friendly. Everybody loves a well-played bard.
<P>
So long, and enjoy your bard.
</td></tr>
